english:
  title: 'Memorial Inscription for the Combined Rites at Yeongneung: Conferring Posthumous Names Upon King Gyeongjo and Queen Heon-suk'
  author: Park Ho
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your servant has heard that the combined offering represents the shared ritual of the realm, while the divided sacrifice upholds the eternal custom of dynasties past. How much more, then, should we extend our deepest reverence, having inherited the luminous virtue of our forebears.

    Reverently considering: King Gyeongjo, the Honored Great King, embodied reverence and caution, magnanimity and breadth. His virtue delighting in life brought forth bounty that nourished his age and extends beyond, while his teachings of kinship harmony grow ever deeper, blessing generations without end.

    Queen Heon-suk, the Honored consort of the Kim clan, gathered within herself chastity and virtue, her heart dwelling in gentleness and compliance. She ordered the affairs of the inner palace with correctness and revealed the transforming way throughout the realm. Her bearing shone with solemn dignity, her conduct illuminated by honored service.

    Reflecting upon this: your humble heir has received the great inheritance, and with reverent sincerity has made offerings; yet the sacred rites of ancestral veneration remain incomplete. Therefore we now perform the combined sacrifice before our forebears, honoring too their transition to the ancestral shrine.

    We dispatch our envoy [name] with vice-envoy [name], bearing respectfully the prepared offerings—swine and fragrant grain, incense vessels and aromatic branches, fine vegetables and precious gifts—to conduct the sacred feast with utmost propriety. We present this memorial inscription to confer upon the Great King the posthumous name of [name], and upon the Queen consort the posthumous name of [name]. May your celestial wisdom bend favorably upon our most sincere devotion, that the spirits of the nine ancestral temples grant us the blessings of a thousand years.
  footnotes:
    - Hegapsae (협제, 祫祭) refers to the combined sacrifice, a grand ancestral rite performed in conjunction with the conferral of posthumous names.
    - The nine ancestral temples (구묘, 九廟) represent the complete ancestral lineage honored in Korean royal ritual tradition.
